<task id="002" project="spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5">
  <metadata>
    <title>D1-02 Extend `RagSearchOptions` with `sessionId` filter (additive parameter) + route `RagService.SearchAsync()` to `spaarke-session-files` index</title>
    <status>complete</status>
    <estimated-effort>2 hours</estimated-effort>
    <actual-effort>1.5 hours (sub-agent authoring; main session runs build/test/publish-size + commit)</actual-effort>
    <assigned>AI Agent</assigned>
    <started>2026-06-04</started>
    <completed>2026-06-04</completed>
    <phase>Phase 1 — Platform Extensions</phase>
    <wave>P1-G2 (parallel with task 003)</wave>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
    <dependencies>001 (index schema; smoke-test only — code change can be authored against schema spec)</dependencies>
    <tags>bff, rag, additive</tags>
    <rigor-level>FULL</rigor-level>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Extend the existing `RagSearchOptions` record with an additive `SessionId` property and
    route `RagService.SearchAsync()` to the new `spaarke-session-files` Azure AI Search index
    when `SessionId` is provided. The existing tenant-scoped knowledge-index path (the
    customer-corpus search used by the existing Summarize wizard query) MUST remain
    functionally identical when `SessionId` is absent — this is the binding
    backward-compatibility contract for R5 Phase 1.

    Per ADR-014, the session-files index documents carry BOTH `tenantId` AND `sessionId`.
    The filter built inside `BuildSearchOptions` MUST AND both fields when routing
    session-scoped, so a session query in tenant A can never leak across to tenant B (the
    existing `tenantId eq '...'` filter is preserved, and `sessionId eq '...'` is added).

    This task is REUSE-FIRST per R5 CLAUDE.md §3.1: MUST extend the existing
    `RagSearchOptions` record (defined in `IRagService.cs`) and the existing `RagService`
    class — do NOT introduce a parallel `SessionRagSearchOptions` / `SessionRagService`.
    The task introduces ZERO new feature flags (R5 CLAUDE.md §3.2). DI registrations, if
    any are needed (none expected for this task), MUST go inside
    `Infrastructure/DI/AnalysisServicesModule.cs` per R5 CLAUDE.md §3.3 + ADR-010.

    The session-files index name MUST be admin-overridable via existing
    `AiSearchOptions` configuration (mirror the `KnowledgeIndexName` /
    `RagReferencesIndexName` pattern at `src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Options/AiSearchOptions.cs`).
    Default: `"spaarke-session-files"`.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior .NET developer with Azure AI Search experience. Deep familiarity with
    `RagService`'s hybrid-search pipeline (keyword + vector + semantic), the
    `IKnowledgeDeploymentService`-driven multi-tenant index routing, and the OData filter
    builder in `BuildSearchOptions`. Strong instinct for additive, backward-compatible
    extensions to widely-consumed record types.
  </role>

  <goal>
    `RagSearchOptions` exposes a new optional `SessionId` (string?) initializer.
    `RagService.SearchAsync(query, options, ct)` routes to the `spaarke-session-files`
    index (resolved via `AiSearchOptions.SessionFilesIndexName`, default
    `"spaarke-session-files"`) when `options.SessionId` is non-empty, and applies a
    `tenantId eq '...' and sessionId eq '...'` filter (preserving existing
    privilege-group + tag + entity-scope filters as applicable; see §Existing-Filter-Preservation
    in design notes). When `options.SessionId` is null/empty, the method's behavior is
    BYTE-FOR-BYTE identical to current — the existing
    `IKnowledgeDeploymentService.GetSearchClientAsync(tenantId, ct)` path is used,
    customer-corpus queries (e.g., R3/R4 wizard `streamSummarize()` callers) remain
    unaffected. Unit tests demonstrate both code paths. BFF builds clean; publish-size
    delta ≤ +0.1 MB per task budget; existing wizard tests still pass.
  </goal>

